{{good article}} {{infobox military unit |unit_name=No. 77 Wing RAAF |image=[[File:110299Beaufighter1945.jpg|300px]] |caption=Beaufighter of No. 31 Squadron, part of No.&nbsp;77 Wing, landing on Tarakan airstrip, Borneo, 1945 |dates=1943–46 |country=Australia |branch=[[Royal Australian Air Force]] |role=Attack |size=Three flying squadrons |command_structure=[[Australian First Tactical Air Force|First Tactical Air Force]] |battles=World War II * [[Battle of Noemfoor]] * [[Battle of Leyte]] * [[Battle of Tarakan (1945)|Battle of Tarakan]] * [[Battle of North Borneo]] |notable_commanders=[[Charles Read (RAAF officer)|Charles Read]] |aircraft_attack=[[Vultee A-31 Vengeance|Vengeance]]; [[Douglas A-20 Havoc|Boston]]; [[Bristol Beaufighter|Beaufighter]] }}
'''No. 77 Wing''' was a [[Royal Australian Air Force]] (RAAF) [[Wing (military aviation unit)|wing]] of World War II. It formed part of No.&nbsp;10 Operational Group (later the [[Australian First Tactical Air Force]]) at its establishment in November 1943, when it comprised three [[Squadron (aviation)|squadron]]s equipped with [[Vultee A-31 Vengeance|Vultee Vengeance]] dive bombers. No.&nbsp;77 Wing commenced operations in early 1944, flying out of [[Nadzab]], Papua New Guinea. Soon afterwards, however, the Vengeance units were withdrawn from combat and replaced with squadrons flying [[Douglas A-20 Havoc|Douglas Bostons]], [[Bristol Beaufighter]]s and [[Bristol Beaufort]]s. The wing saw action in the assaults on [[Battle of Noemfoor|Noemfoor]], [[Battle of Tarakan (1945)|Tarakan]], and [[Battle of North Borneo|North Borneo]], by which time it was an all-Beaufighter formation made up of [[No. 22 Squadron RAAF|Nos.&nbsp;22]], [[No. 30 Squadron RAAF|30]] and [[No. 31 Squadron RAAF|31 Squadrons]]. It was to have taken part in the [[Battle of Balikpapan (1945)|Battle of Balikpapan]] in June 1945, but unsuitable landing grounds meant that the Beaufighter units were withdrawn to [[Morotai]], sitting out the remainder of the war before returning to Australia, where they disbanded, along with the wing headquarters, in 1946.
==History== [[File:OG0680Vengeance1944.jpg|left|thumb|250px|Vengeance dive bombers of No.&nbsp;21 Squadron at Nadzab, Papua New Guinea, in February 1944]] No. 77 Wing formed the [[Close air support|attack]] component of No.&nbsp;10 Operational Group (No.&nbsp;10 OG), which was established on 13&nbsp;November 1943. The group was to act as a mobile strike force capable of supporting Allied ground and naval units while they advanced against the [[Empire of Japan|Japanese]] in the [[South West Pacific theatre of World War II|South West Pacific Area]] (SWPA), as distinct from the RAAF's [[RAAF area commands|area commands]] in Northern Australia, which had a geographically based static defence function.<ref>Odgers, [http://www.awm.gov.au/cms_images/histories/27/chapters/12.pdf ''Air War Against Japan'', pp.182–183,198–200]</ref><ref name="Stephens pp.168-170">Stephens, ''The Royal Australian Air Force'', pp.168–170</ref> Led by [[Wing Commander (rank)|Wing Commander]] E.G. Fyfe, No.&nbsp;77 Wing consisted of three flying squadrons operating [[Vultee A-31 Vengeance|Vultee Vengeance]] dive bombers, and various ancillary units. The Vengeances, which had only recently been acquired by Australia, equipped [[No. 21 Squadron RAAF|Nos.&nbsp; 21]], [[No. 23 Squadron RAAF|23]] and [[No. 24 Squadron RAAF|24 Squadrons]]. They were to be protected on their attack missions by No.&nbsp;10 OG's [[Fighter aircraft|fighter]] component, [[No. 78 Wing RAAF|No.&nbsp;78 Wing]], operating [[Curtis P-40 Warhawk|Curtiss Kittyhawks]].<ref>Odgers, ''Air War Against Japan'', pp.182–183</ref>
Headquartered at [[Nadzab]], Papua New Guinea, No.&nbsp;77 Wing only became fully operational on 18&nbsp;February 1944, following the arrival of Nos.&nbsp;21 and 23 Squadrons from [[Lowood, Queensland|Lowood]], Queensland. However No.&nbsp;24 Squadron, which was already based in the theatre of operations, was able to carry out its first sortie on 17&nbsp;January, bombing targets along [[Shaggy Ridge]] in support of the [[Australian 7th Division]]. Throughout February the Vengeances, escorted by No.&nbsp;78 Wing Kittyhawks, concentrated on harassing the retreating [[20th Division (Imperial Japanese Army)|Japanese 20th Division]], and attacking enemy airfields in the [[Madang Province]].<ref>Odgers, ''Air War Against Japan'', pp.188–192</ref> In March, a decision was made to withdraw the dive bombers from operations due to their inferiority to newer equipment. Three RAAF squadrons—[[No. 22 Squadron RAAF|No.&nbsp;22]] flying [[Douglas A-20 Havoc|Douglas Bostons]], [[No. 30 Squadron RAAF|No.&nbsp;30]] flying [[Bristol Beaufighter]]s, and one other from [[No. 9 Operational Group RAAF|No.&nbsp;9 Operational Group]] flying [[Bristol Beaufort]]s—were assigned to the wing as replacements.<ref>Odgers, ''Air War Against Japan'', pp.196–198</ref>
[[File:22 Sqn (AWM OG1732).jpg|thumb|left|250px|Boston of No.&nbsp;22 Squadron being prepared for a sortie at Noemfoor in October 1944]] Operating with its new squadrons and aircraft, No.&nbsp; 77 Wing took part in the [[Battle of Noemfoor]], commencing in June 1944. Wing headquarters relocated to [[Noemfoor Island]] in July, followed by Nos.&nbsp;22 and 30 Squadrons the next month.<ref>Odgers, [http://www.awm.gov.au/cms_images/histories/27/chapters/15.pdf ''Air War Against Japan'', pp.237–242]</ref><ref>Johnston, ''Whispering Death'', p.377</ref> This was No.&nbsp;77 Wing's composition on 25&nbsp;October 1944, when No.&nbsp;10 OG's name was changed to the [[Australian First Tactical Air Force]], ostensibly to emphasise "the formation's impressive size and ambitious purpose".<ref name="Stephens pp.168-170"/><ref name="Odgers pp.297-299">Odgers, [http://www.awm.gov.au/cms_images/histories/27/chapters/17.pdf ''Air War Against Japan'', pp.297–299]</ref> That month, the wing's aircraft were credited with sinking 24 enemy transport ships and barges in support of the Allied landings during the [[Battle of Leyte]].<ref>Odgers, ''Air War Against Japan'', pp.302–303</ref> In November, the wing advanced to the island of [[Morotai]], where it attacked Japanese airfields, shipping, and infrastructure on [[Sulawesi|Celebes]].<ref>Odgers, [http://www.awm.gov.au/cms_images/histories/27/chapters/18.pdf ''Air War Against Japan'', p.309]</ref> By the end of the year, Wing Commander [[Charles Read (RAAF officer)|Charles Read]] had taken over command of No.&nbsp;77 Wing,<ref name="Gillison">Gillison, [http://www.awm.gov.au/cms_images/histories/26/chapters/30.pdf ''Royal Australian Air Force'', p.647n]</ref> and the formation's complement had been augmented by [[No. 31 Squadron RAAF|No.&nbsp;31 Squadron]], a Beaufighter unit previously based in [[Darwin, Northern Territory|Darwin]], Northern Territory, as part of [[North-Western Area Command (RAAF)|North-Western Area Command]].<ref name="Odgers pp.297-299"/><ref>Odgers, [http://www.awm.gov.au/cms_images/histories/27/chapters/23.pdf ''Air War Against Japan'', p.379]</ref> No.&nbsp;22 Squadron was withdrawn to Noemfoor in December to re-equip with Beaufighters; upon its return No.&nbsp;77 Wing became an all-Beaufighter formation, operating three squadrons of the type.<ref>Odgers, ''Air War Against Japan'', pp.311–312</ref>
During the first week of January 1945, No. &nbsp;77 Wing's aircraft undertook 142 missions against targets in [[Halmahera]], Celebes, and Morotai.<ref>Odgers, ''Air War Against Japan'', p.384</ref> In May, the Beaufighters provided air cover during Operation Oboe One, the [[Battle of Tarakan (1945)|Battle of Tarakan]].<ref>Odgers, [http://www.awm.gov.au/cms_images/histories/27/chapters/27.pdf ''Air War Against Japan'', pp.453–459]</ref> In the days leading up to Operation Oboe Six, the [[Battle of North Borneo]], No.&nbsp;77 Wing surgically attacked enemy targets at [[Labuan]], sometimes within only 100&nbsp;metres of Allied demolition teams laying charges to breach obstacles on the beach prior to the landings. Read personally led No.&nbsp;31 Squadron into action during the battle on 10&nbsp;June 1945.<ref>Odgers, [http://www.awm.gov.au/cms_images/histories/27/chapters/28.pdf ''Air War Against Japan'', pp.469–471]</ref> He became the first RAAF pilot to land at the newly operational [[Tarakan Island|Tarakan]] airfield on 28&nbsp;June. The following month, No.&nbsp;77 Wing was to have taken part in the final Allied offensive of the [[Borneo campaign (1945)|Borneo Campaign]], Operation Oboe Two, the [[Battle of Balikpapan (1945)|Battle of Balikpapan]]. However Tarakan proved to be unsuitable for the Beaufighters to operate from, and they were withdrawn to Morotai, where they largely sat out the rest of the Pacific War.<ref>Odgers, [http://www.awm.gov.au/cms_images/histories/27/chapters/29.pdf ''Air War Against Japan'', pp.482–483]</ref> No.&nbsp;71 Wing headquarters transferred to [[Deniliquin Airport|Deniliquin]], New South Wales, in December 1945,<ref name=DVA>[http://clik.dva.gov.au/history-library/part-3-order-battle/ch-2-order-battle-air-force/s-2-headquarters Order of Battle&nbsp;– Air Force&nbsp;– Headquarters] at [[Department of Veterans' Affairs (Australia)|Department of Veterans' Affairs]]. Retrieved on 12 July 2015.</ref> and was joined there by Nos.&nbsp;22 and 30 Squadrons, both of which disbanded in August 1946.<ref>[http://www.awm.gov.au/units/unit_11057.asp 22 Squadron RAAF] at [[Australian War Memorial]]. Retrieved on 12 July 2015.</ref><ref>[http://www.awm.gov.au/units/unit_11065.asp 30 Squadron RAAF] at Australian War Memorial. Retrieved on 12 July 2015.</ref> No.&nbsp;31 Squadron transferred from Morotai to [[RAAF Base Williamtown|Williamtown]], where it disbanded in July 1946.<ref>[http://www.awm.gov.au/units/unit_11067.asp 31 Squadron RAAF] at Australian War Memorial. Retrieved on 12 July 2015.</ref> No.&nbsp;71 Wing headquarters disbanded at Deniliquin in November.<ref name=DVA/>
